Introduction

For this week’s homework, I did an analysis of Wikipedia pages related to the Green Gang, a gang active during the Chinese civil war and influential at the time.

pttTestFunction <- function(URL, filename)
{
  #URL   = "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Gang"
  html  = read_html(URL)
  title = html_nodes(html, "a")
  href  = html_attr(title, "href")
  data = data.frame(title = toUTF8(html_text(title)),
                    href = href)
  data = data[c(42:52),]
  getContent <- function(x) {
    url  = paste0("https://en.wikipedia.org", x)
    tag  = html_node(read_html(url), 'div#bodyContent')
    text = toUTF8(html_text(tag))
  }
  #getContent(data$href[1])
  allText = sapply(data$href, getContent)
  allText
  #out <- file(filename, "w", encoding="BIG-5") 
  write.table(allText, filename) 
  #close(out) 
}


id = c(1:10)
URL =paste0("https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Gang")
filename = paste0(id, ".txt")
mapply(pttTestFunction, 
       URL = URL, filename = filename)
rm(list=ls(all.names = TRUE))
library(NLP)
library(tm)
library(jiebaRD)
library(jiebaR)
library(RColorBrewer)
library(wordcloud)
filenames <- list.files(getwd(), pattern="*.txt")
files <- lapply(filenames, readLines)
docs <- Corpus(VectorSource(files))
toSpace <- content_transformer(function(x, pattern) {
  return (gsub(pattern, " ", x))
}
)
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeWords,stopwords("english"))
docs <- tm_map(docs, removePunctuation)
docs <- tm_map(docs, removeNumbers)
docs <- tm_map(docs, stripWhitespace)
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "the")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "The")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "U")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "UA")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "A")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "ISBN")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "In")
docs <- tm_map(docs, toSpace, "Retrieved")
mixseg = worker()
jieba_tokenizer=function(d){
  unlist(segment(d[[1]],mixseg))
}
seg = lapply(docs, jieba_tokenizer)
freqFrame = as.data.frame(table(unlist(seg)))

wordcloud(freqFrame$Var1,freqFrame$Freq,
          scale=c(5,0.1),min.freq=50,max.words=150,
          random.order=TRUE, random.color=FALSE, 
          rot.per=.1, colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"),
          ordered.colors=FALSE,use.r.layout=FALSE,
          fixed.asp=TRUE)

Conclusions

As expected, most of the most often seen words are words related to either crime or the Chinese Civil War (opium, sex, and Chiang Kai-shek all making appearances). This is more or less in line with what would be expected.
